    "narrative": "Our primary objective today is capitalizing on the high-SB environment created by slow-working opposition, pushing **Jose Caballero** to the top of our value chart with a 77.16 score. While his #8 spot in the lineup is a drag on his efficiency, his matchup against the southpaw Springs, combined with the extreme boost for his elite sprint speed against a slow-to-the-plate pitcher, makes him an essential start. Similarly, **Mickey Moniak** is positioned for a breakout game batting second against V\u00e1squez. His 75.98 score is bolstered significantly by a massive 19% boost from the SP skill gap and a favorable platoon profile, making him the premier offensive weapon in the lineup today. **Giancarlo Stanton** also remains a locked-in \"Strong\" play at 67.71; the combination of the 4.60 xERA opposing starter and a #4 hole projection provides a high floor for counting stats.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the morning was keeping **Vinnie Pasquantino** on the bench. His projection of 39.32 fell just short of our 40.0 \"Zebras\" floor, primarily due to the daunting 2.45 xERA of the opposing pitcher, Kay. Despite a solid base projection, the combination of a sharp decline in SP-specific performance expectations and a detrimental platoon split rendered him too risky to start in a limited-cap format. Meanwhile, **Max Muncy** (61.96) remains a solid core piece today; his platoon advantage against Weathers and the additional value extracted from his #5 spot and the potential for stolen bases against a favorable delivery rhythm solidify his place in the middle of our order. \n\nWe are monitoring the **Tyler Soderstrom** slot (52.89) closely, as he remains in the marginal category; while his power profile is useful, the dynamic platoon penalty against the left-handed Weathers makes him a volatile asset. **Zach McKinstry** (49.64) similarly rests on the razor\u2019s edge of our start threshold. We have opted to prioritize the high-SB ceiling of **Jose Caballero** and **Mickey Moniak** today, ensuring we remain aggressive in the scarcest category while avoiding the high-ERA traps that suppressed the values of **Vinnie Pasquantino** and our other bench assets like **Corbin Carroll**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Josh Naylor**. No major weather risks are flagged, but we are keeping a close eye on final lineup confirmations for any late-inning defensive shifts that could impact our bottom-of-the-order production.",
